## C. System reliability — infra failures

### C1. SPA invisible to search engines
**Severity:** P0 (growth) · **First observed:** Month 1 · **Status:** Resolved (in flight)

**Trigger.** Quantis launched as a pure client-rendered SPA. Googlebot received an empty shell on every public page. Organic acquisition was structurally impossible.

**Symptom.** Zero organic traffic 60 days post-launch despite content marketing.

**Detection.** Search Console showed zero indexed content pages. Direct curl of public URLs returned a JS shell.

**Mitigation.** Migration of the marketing surface to Next.js static rendering. The application surface remains client-rendered behind auth.

### C2. Stripe webhook race on first-purchase credit grant
**Severity:** P0 · **First observed:** Month 2 · **Status:** Resolved

**Trigger.** A user pays, the Stripe webhook arrives before the redirect-back finishes, and the credit-grant code path fires twice — or, in a worse race, not at all.

**Symptom.** A small fraction of paying users were either double-credited or never credited.

**Detection.** Reconciliation job comparing Stripe's `payment_intent.succeeded` events against the `webhook_events` table.

**Mitigation.** Webhook handler is now strictly idempotent on `event.id` with a unique constraint. The redirect-back path is read-only — credit grants happen only on webhook delivery.

### C3. PDF generation memory blowup
**Severity:** P1 · **First observed:** Month 3 · **Status:** Resolved

**Trigger.** Long validations with extensive risk-factor sections caused the headless renderer to exceed the edge function's memory limit.

**Symptom.** Document generation fails for ~2% of validations.

**Detection.** Sentry error spike on the `documents` endpoint.

**Mitigation.** Streamed rendering with bounded chunks. Documents above a size threshold are generated asynchronously with a polling endpoint.

### C4. Supabase RLS misconfiguration on a join table
**Severity:** P0 · **First observed:** Month 1 · **Status:** Resolved (caught in staging, never reached production)

**Trigger.** A new join table linking validations to documents was added without row-level security policies. Cross-tenant read was theoretically possible.

**Symptom.** None in production — the gap was caught by a pre-deploy schema linter.

**Detection.** Custom CI check enumerates every table in the public schema and fails the build if any lack an RLS policy.

**Mitigation.** RLS-required CI gate is now standard for every schema change.

